  <datafield tag="545" ind1="0" ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="a">Donald A. Johnston III, born in Virginia in 1944, had a long legal career in Michigan that included a law degree from Wayne State University, thirteen years on the staff of the Kent County Prosecuting Attorney, and more than three decades as judge on the 61st District Court and the 17th Circuit Court. Johnston presided over dozens of trials in the greater Grand Rapids area, primarily criminal cases, and was extensively involved in the activities of the Michigan State Bar, the Michigan Judicial Institute, and Governor Rick Snyder's Council on Law Enforcement and Reinvention (CLEAR). In October 2015, Johnston was reappointed to this position for a two-year term to commence January 1, 2016.</subfield>
  </datafield>
  <datafield tag="520" ind1="2" ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="a">Records documenting the tenure of Donald A. Johnston on the benches of two Michigan courts, primarily addressing his rulings on criminal cases heard in the 17th Circuit Court between 1989 and 2012. Includes notes on the background of each trial and the sentence levied, materials on cases later heard in appellate courts, Johnston's responses to requests for special alternative incarceration, and correspondence. Also a court notice of 2015 re-appointment as Chief Judge.</subfield>
  </datafield>
